fonline access with authorization2star  aWhen the medievals spoke of "last things" they were sometimes referring to events, such as the millennium or the appearance of the Antichrist, that would come to all of humanity or at the end of time. But they also meant the last things that would come to each individual separately—not just the place, Heaven, Hell, or Purgatory, to which their souls would go but also the accounting, the calling to reckoning, that would come at the end of life. At different periods in the Middle Ages one or the other of these sorts of "last things" tended to be dominant, but both coexisted throughout. In Last Things, Caroline Walker Bynum and Paul Freedman bring together eleven essays that focus on the competing eschatologies of the Middle Ages and on the ways in which they expose different sensibilities, different theories of the human person, and very different understandings of the body, of time, of the end. Exploring such themes as the significance of dying and the afterlife, apocalyptic time, and the eschatological imagination, each essay in the volume enriches our understanding of the eschatological awarenesses of the European Middle Ages.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 4aReligious Studies. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aEuropean History.  aHistory.  aMedieval and Renaissance Studies.  aReligion.  aReligious Studies.  aWorld History.1 aBackman, Clifford R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBynum, Caroline Walker, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBynum, Caroline Walker, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDaniel, E. Randolph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFreed